Credit Card Users Churn Prediction¶

Problem Statement¶

Business Context¶

The Thera bank recently saw a steep decline in the number of users of their credit card, credit cards are a good source of income for banks because of different kinds of fees charged by the banks like annual fees, balance transfer fees, and cash advance fees, late payment fees, foreign transaction fees, and others. Some fees are charged to every user irrespective of usage, while others are charged under specified circumstances.

Customers’ leaving credit cards services would lead bank to loss, so the bank wants to analyze the data of customers and identify the customers who will leave their credit card services and reason for same – so that bank could improve upon those areas

You as a Data scientist at Thera bank need to come up with a classification model that will help the bank improve its services so that customers do not renounce their credit cards

Data Description¶

  • CLIENTNUM: Client number. Unique identifier for the customer holding the account
  • Attrition_Flag: Internal event (customer activity) variable - if the account is closed then "Attrited Customer" else "Existing Customer"
  • Customer_Age: Age in Years
  • Gender: Gender of the account holder
  • Dependent_count: Number of dependents
  • Education_Level: Educational Qualification of the account holder - Graduate, High School, Unknown, Uneducated, College(refers to college student), Post-Graduate, Doctorate
  • Marital_Status: Marital Status of the account holder
  • Income_Category: Annual Income Category of the account holder
  • Card_Category: Type of Card
  • Months_on_book: Period of relationship with the bank (in months)
  • Total_Relationship_Count: Total no. of products held by the customer
  • Months_Inactive_12_mon: No. of months inactive in the last 12 months
  • Contacts_Count_12_mon: No. of Contacts in the last 12 months
  • Credit_Limit: Credit Limit on the Credit Card
  • Total_Revolving_Bal: Total Revolving Balance on the Credit Card
  • Avg_Open_To_Buy: Open to Buy Credit Line (Average of last 12 months)
  • Total_Amt_Chng_Q4_Q1: Change in Transaction Amount (Q4 over Q1)
  • Total_Trans_Amt: Total Transaction Amount (Last 12 months)
  • Total_Trans_Ct: Total Transaction Count (Last 12 months)
  • Total_Ct_Chng_Q4_Q1: Change in Transaction Count (Q4 over Q1)
  • Avg_Utilization_Ratio: Average Card Utilization Ratio

What Is a Revolving Balance?¶

  • If we don't pay the balance of the revolving credit account in full every month, the unpaid portion carries over to the next month. That's called a revolving balance
What is the Average Open to buy?¶
  • 'Open to Buy' means the amount left on your credit card to use. Now, this column represents the average of this value for the last 12 months.
What is the Average utilization Ratio?¶
  • The Avg_Utilization_Ratio represents how much of the available credit the customer spent. This is useful for calculating credit scores.
Relation b/w Avg_Open_To_Buy, Credit_Limit and Avg_Utilization_Ratio:¶
  • ( Avg_Open_To_Buy / Credit_Limit ) + Avg_Utilization_Ratio = 1

Analyzing the statistical summary of each column in order:

  • CLIENTNUM is an identifier and can be removed from the data before proceeding with modeling.
  • Attrition_Flag is our independent variable that is either Existing Customer or Attrited Customer, with just those two unique values.
  • Customer_age: The age of the customers range from 26 to 73 with average age around 46 years old.
  • Gender: The gender column stores two values with the majority being F for female.
  • Dependent_count: On average the clients have 2.3 dependents and range from 0 to 5 maximum.
  • Education_Level: There are 6 unique Education levels with the most common one being Graduate which are 3128 customers; there are also a considerable number of missing values which have to be dealt with.
  • Marital_Status: There are 3 unique types of Marital Status and the most common is Married, followed by Single and then Divorced and 749 missing values.
  • Income_Category: There are 6 unique Income Categories, the most common one being Less than $40K. There exists an unusual one called abc which has to be cleaned before proceeding.
  • Card_Category: There are 4 unique Card categories and the most frequently occurring one is Blue. The others are Silver, Gold and Platinum.
  • The categorical variables can be explored in more detail in univariate analysis since we can only see the mode in this summary.
  • Months_on_book: The average period of relationship with the bank is 35.9 months ranging from a minimum of 13 months to maximum 56 months. The median is also very close to the mean at 36 months.
  • Total_Relationship_Count: On average customers hold 3.8 products with the bank, with minimum 1 and maximum 6.
  • Months_Inactive_12_mon: The average number of months a customer is inactive in the last 12 months is 2.31, ranging between 0 months of inactivity to 6 months of activity ie half the year.
  • Contacts_Count_12_mon: The average number of contacts between the customer and the bank in the last 12 months is 2.455, also ranging from 0 to maximum 6 contacts.
  • Credit_Limit: The average credit limit is 8631.95, with median being 4549 and maximum being 34516 with indicates possible right skewness of the data.
  • Total_Revolving_Bal: The average balance that customers carry from one month to the next is 1162.81, ranging between a minimum of 0 to maximum 2517.
  • Avg_Open_To_Buy: The average amount left on the credit card to use across customers is 7469.140, with a minimum value of 3 and maximum of 34516. 75% of the customers have an average Open To Buy value of 9859 or less. This indicates that the data might be right skewed.
  • Total_Amt_Chng_Q4_Q1: The mean ratio of the total transaction count in 4th and 1st quarter is 0.76, ranging between a minimum and maximum of 0 and 3.397 respectively.
  • Total_Trans_Amt: The average total transaction amount in the last 12 months is 4404.08, meanwhile the median is. 3899.000. However, the range of the total transaction amount is quite large between 510 and 18484, maximum being much higher than the 3rd quartile which means the data is potentially right skewed.
  • Total_Trans_Ct: The average total transaction count in the last 12 months is 64.85, ranging between 10 and 139.
  • Total_Ct_Chng_Q4_Q1: The mean ratio of the total transaction amount in 4th quarter and 1st quarter is 0.71 and a similar median of 0.702. The minimum value is 0 and maximum 3.714, potentially a right skewed distribution.
  • Avg_Utilization_Ratio: The average available credit the customer spent is 0.275, while the data has a wide range between 0 and 0.999

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)¶

  • EDA is an important part of any project involving data.
  • It is important to investigate and understand the data better before building a model with it.
  • A few questions have been mentioned below which will help you approach the analysis in the right manner and generate insights from the data.
  • A thorough analysis of the data, in addition to the questions mentioned below, should be done.

Questions:

  1. How is the total transaction amount distributed?
  2. What is the distribution of the level of education of customers?
  3. What is the distribution of the level of income of customers?
  4. How does the change in transaction amount between Q4 and Q1 (total_ct_change_Q4_Q1) vary by the customer's account status (Attrition_Flag)?

# function to plot a boxplot and a histogram along the same scale.


def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to the show density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a triangle will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram
In [43]:
# function to create labeled barplots


def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

# function to plot stacked bar chart

def stacked_barplot(data, predictor, target):
    """
    Print the category counts and plot a stacked bar chart

    data: dataframe
    predictor: independent variable
    target: target variable
    """
    count = data[predictor].nunique()
    sorter = data[target].value_counts().index[-1]
    tab1 = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], margins=True).sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    print(tab1)
    print("-" * 120)
    tab = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], normalize="index").sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    tab.plot(kind="bar", stacked=True, figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    plt.legend(
        loc="lower left", frameon=False,
    )
    plt.legend(loc="upper left", bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))
    plt.show()

### Function to plot distributions

def distribution_plot_wrt_target(data, predictor, target):

    fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(12, 10))

    target_uniq = data[target].unique()

    axs[0, 0].set_title("Distribution of target for target=" + str(target_uniq[0]))
    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == target_uniq[0]],
        x=predictor,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 0],
        color="teal",
    )

    axs[0, 1].set_title("Distribution of target for target=" + str(target_uniq[1]))
    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == target_uniq[1]],
        x=predictor,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 1],
        color="orange",
    )

    axs[1, 0].set_title("Boxplot w.r.t target")
    sns.boxplot(data=data, x=target, y=predictor, ax=axs[1, 0], palette="gist_rainbow")

    axs[1, 1].set_title("Boxplot (without outliers) w.r.t target")
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data,
        x=target,
        y=predictor,
        ax=axs[1, 1],
        showfliers=False,
        palette="gist_rainbow",
    )

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Correlation Observations¶

In [116]:
#Correlation heatmap to analyze relationship between all numerical variables
cols_list = data.select_dtypes(include=np.number).columns.tolist()
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 7))
sns.heatmap(
    data[cols_list].corr(), annot=True, vmin=-1, vmax=1, fmt=".2f", cmap="Spectral"
)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

From the correlation matrix, we can see several strong correlations and some weak ones. Below is a summary by column:

  • Attrition Flag: We are most interested in seeing which columns are strongly correlated with this value because it is our dependent variable.
    • Total_Trans_Ct: The strongest negative correlation with attrition meaning that higher the total transaction count, less likely they are to attrite but the correlation is only -0.37.
    • Total_Ct_Chng_Q4_Q1: The correlation is -0.29 which suggests that customers with a higher change in transaction count between Q4 and Q1 are less likely to attrite.
    • Total_Revolving_Bal: With a correlation of -0.26, this suggests that customers with a higher revolving balance are less likely to attrite.
    • Contacts_Count_12_mon: Positively correlated (0.20) indicating that the more contacts the customer had with the bank in the last 12 months, the more likely they are to attrite, which is strange but could indicate dissatisfaction of service.
    The Attrition Flag seems to have a handful of weak to medium influencing variables, a combination of which is likely to give the best outcome when we build the model.
  • Customer Age has a very strong correlation of 0.79 with months on book, which is as expected since the older customers tend to have a long relationship with the bank.
  • Credit Limit and Avg Open to Buy have a perfect correlation of 1.00, which is understandable and makes sense since Avg Open to Buy must be derived from the available credit, hence it is a function of the Credit Limit.
  • Total Transaction Amount and Total Transaction Count have a positive correlation of 0.81. This logically makes sense since the higher the number of transactions, the higher the total transaction amount tends to be.
  • Total Revolving Balance and Avg Utilization Ratio have a positive correlation of 0.62, indicating that customers that have a higher balance also have a higher utilization rate.
  • Avg Utilization Ratio is also fairly strongly negatively correlated with Credit_Limit (-0.48) and Avg_Open_To_Buy (-0.54) which is expected since they are related mathematically and are a function of how much credit limit is used.

Bivariate questions¶

  1. How does the change in transaction amount between Q4 and Q1 (total_ct_change_Q4_Q1) vary by the customer's account status (Attrition_Flag)?

Summarizing the findings from the bivariate analysis, total total count change between Q4 and Q1 differs significantly between customers who attrited and those who didn’t, with attrited customers having a lower median and spread. The median count change for attrited customers is around 0.5, while it’s about 0.7 for those who continued, indicating that a higher count change reduces the likelihood of attrition. This suggests that total count change is a strong predictor of attrition.

  1. How does the number of months a customer was inactive in the last 12 months (Months_Inactive_12_mon) vary by the customer's account status (Attrition_Flag)?

Summarizing the findings from the bivariate analysis, the number of inactive months in the last 12 months shows varying patterns, with customers having 3-5 months of inactivity more likely to attrite, while those with 1 month inactive are more likely to stay. There is no clear linear correlation, as high inactivity does not always indicate attrition. Overall, Months Inactive is a useful variable when combined with other factors to predict attrition.

  1. What are the attributes that have a strong correlation with each other?

Summarizing the findings from the correlation heatmap, the attributes show strong relationships with each other are:

  • Attrition Flag has the strongest negative correlation with Total Transaction Count (-0.37), meaning more transactions are associated with lower attrition. Other variables it is correlated with are Total Ct Chng Q4-Q1 (-0.29), Total Revolving Balance (-0.26), and a positive correlation with Contacts Count 12 mon (0.20), which may reflect dissatisfaction.
  • Customer Age has a strong correlation with Months on Book (0.79), indicating older customers have longer relationships with the bank.
  • Credit Limit and Avg Open to Buy have a perfect correlation (1.00), because they are derived from the other.
  • Total Transaction Amount and Total Transaction Count are strongly correlated (0.81), intuitively linking more transactions to higher transaction amounts.
  • Total Revolving Balance and Avg Utilization Ratio are positively correlated (0.62), showing that higher balances lead to higher utilization rates. Avg Utilization Ratio is also negatively correlated with Credit Limit (-0.48) and Avg Open to Buy (-0.54), reflecting their mathematical relationships as mentioned in the data dictionary.

Model Building¶

Model evaluation criterion¶

Model can make wrong predictions as:

  • Predicting a customer will attrite and the customer doesn't attrite
  • Predicting a customer will not attrite and the customer attrites

Which case is more important?

  • Predicting that customer will not attrite but he attrites i.e. losing on a valuable customer or asset.

How to reduce this loss i.e need to reduce False Negatives??

  • Bank would want Recall to be maximized, greater the Recall higher the chances of minimizing false negatives. Hence, the focus should be on increasing Recall or minimizing the false negatives or in other words identifying the true positives(i.e. Class 1) so that the bank can retain their valuable customers by identifying the customers who are at risk of attrition.

Let's define a function to output different metrics (including recall) on the train and test set and a function to show confusion matrix so that we do not have to use the same code repetitively while evaluating models.

In [224]:
# defining a function to compute different metrics to check performance of a classification model built using sklearn
def model_performance_classification_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check classification model performance

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    recall = recall_score(target, pred)  # to compute Recall
    precision = precision_score(target, pred)  # to compute Precision
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred)  # to compute F1-score

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "Accuracy": acc,
            "Recall": recall,
            "Precision": precision,
            "F1": f1

        },
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf

Model Building with original data¶

Sample code for model building with original data

In [226]:
models = []  # Empty list to store all the models
original_performance_train = []
original_performance_val = []

# Appending models into the list
models.append(("Bagging", BaggingClassifier(random_state=1)))
models.append(("Random forest", RandomForestClassifier(random_state=1)))
models.append(("Decision Tree", DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=1)))
models.append(("AdaBoost", AdaBoostClassifier(random_state=1)))
models.append(("GradientBoost", GradientBoostingClassifier(random_state=1)))
models.append(("XGBoost", XGBClassifier(random_state=1)))


# Fit, predict and print the recall for training data
print("\n" "Training Performance:" "\n")
for name, model in models:
    model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    scores = recall_score(y_train, model.predict(X_train))
    original_performance_train.append([name,scores])
    print("{}: {}".format(name, scores))

# Fit, predict and print the recall for validation data
print("\n" "Validation Performance:" "\n")

for name, model in models:
    model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    scores_val = recall_score(y_val, model.predict(X_val))
    original_performance_val.append([name,scores_val])
    print("{}: {}".format(name, scores_val))

Models with original data performance observations:

  • Bagging: The bagging algorithm performs quite well on training set but the difference between the training and validation score may suggest some overfitting, especially with a large difference of 0.1609 between train and validation dataset.
  • Random Forest: The random forest algorithm has a perfect training score of 1.0 which indicates overfitting, especially considering that validation score is only 0.81. The model is most likely memorizing the data instead of generalizing it.
  • Decision Tree: The results are very similar to the random forest algorithm suggesting overfitting and memorization instead of generalization of the rules which is unlikely to perform well on unseen data.
  • AdaBoost: Though the training and validation scores are not as high as the other algorithms, the difference is very small which shows a nearly perfect balance in the algorithm and very good generalization. This algorithm is successfully capturing patterns in the data without overfitting or underfitting and is likely to perform well on unseen data.
  • GradientBoost: The training score is a very good 0.8790 with only a small difference of 0.0054 with the validation score, suggesting that the model has fit the data well and likely to perform well on unseen data.
  • XGBoost: With a perfect training score of 1.0 and a substantial difference of 0.1226 with the validation score, suggesting overfitting but it is still better at generalizing when compared to Random Forest and Decision Tree algorithms in this scenario.

  3. Random Forest Undersampling: While it shows signs of overfitting with a perfect training score, it has shown improvement across datasets and also a high validation score with the undersampled data (0.962) and there are many useful hyperparameters for the tree like max tree depth that can help reduce the overfitting to make it an even better model.

scorer = metrics.make_scorer(metrics.recall_score)

#Calling RandomizedSearchCV
randomized_cv = RandomizedSearchCV(estimator=Model, param_distributions=param_grid, n_jobs = -1, n_iter=50, scoring=scorer, cv=5, random_state=1)

#Fitting parameters in RandomizedSearchCV

Comparing all the models, across training and validation sets, here are the conclusions by machine learning algorithm:

  • XGBoost: The recall is almost perfect and impeccable in both training and data, but the model significantly compromises on balancing Precision and could be identifying too many false positives. While our priority is to minimize recall, having too high a value for false positives isn't ideal either because the company could be focussed on retaining many customers who it thinks will attrite but don't end up attriting.
  • AdaBoost: This model offers the best balance between recall and precision while still priotizing recall, making it a strong all round performing with few trade-offs and good at generalizing even on unseen data.
  • Random Forest: It provides a strong performance in both datasets and also does not sacrifice too much on identifying too many false positives. Though if we had to compare it with AdaBoost, we would probably go for the model with higher Recall, Precision and F1 though they are only slightly higher.

Since we want to maximize Recall, reduce overfitting and focus on not sacrificing the predicting power of the model across different types of erroneous predictions, the model that is chosen in the end is AdaBoost trained with Undersampled data

Feature Importance¶

In [292]:
feature_names = X_train_un.columns
importances =  tuned_adb.feature_importances_
indices = np.argsort(importances)

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 12))
plt.title("Feature Importances")
plt.barh(range(len(indices)), importances[indices], color="violet", align="center")
plt.yticks(range(len(indices)), [feature_names[i] for i in indices])
plt.xlabel("Relative Importance")
plt.show()
  • The top features in the AdaBoost model are
    • Total Transaction Amount which is the most influential by far. This indicates that the total amount made in transactions heavily determines whether a customer will attrite or not, which makes sense in a financial context where transaction behaviour is a key indicator of the type of customer they are.
    • Total Transaction Count is also very influential, similar to Total Transaction Amount and suggests that the frequency of transactions, in addition to the amount of money in the transactions, heavily determine customer behaviour.
    • Total Revolving Balance: The amount of money a customers carries on the credit from month to month is important in determining whether the customer attrites or not, which is logical because it indicates the financial status of the customer and how they interact with the bank and it's products.
    • Change in Transaction count between the last two quarters also plays a role in determining the customer attrition prediction, which shows that the recent customer transaction behaviour, especially if there was a change between Q4 and Q1 is crucial in making a prediction.
  • Some other more moderately important features are Total Relationship Count (indicating the level of involvement and risk the customer has with the bank), the number of inactive months in the last 12 months (a number that indicates how inactive the customer has been with the bank recently which may determine risk), credit limit (an important measure of risk) and the customer's age (which could indicate their financial priorities or preferences). While these factors contributed, they are not as important as the transaction related features.
  • There are other less important features that played a minor role in the overall contribution like dependent count, marital status, income category, card category which are all mostly demographic features that describe the customer rather than their relationship with the bank. They have very low importance compared to other measures.

Business Insights and Conclusions¶

Based on the exploratory data analysis, model performance, features importance and overall analysis, the following are the highlights and recommendations for the business:

  • Transaction behaviour is the most crucial indicator of attrition. The amount that the customers spend in their transactions but also the frequency of the transactions are the most influential factors in determining whether a customer will attrite or not. Monitoring the frequency and amount spend can help the bank flag at-risk customers early and roll out targeted campaigns to incentivize more transactions in terms of volume and frequency in order to retain those customers.
  • Revolving Balance and Credit Limits are also critical indicator of customers' behaviour. The bank can consider offering personal finance advisory services or education programs to their customers with high revolving balances in order to prevent attrition.
  • Change in transaction attrition over time plays a role too. Total Count Change Q4-Q1 and also Number of Inactive months in the last 12 years, which both show customers' behaviour over time in terms of volume and amount of their transactions are moderate determining factors to decide whether they will churn or not, which can be useful for the bank to monitor and implement retention strategies for those customers in order to re-engage them.
  • From the initial data exploration and from the model feature importance, it is clear that the total number of product relationships a customer holds with the bank is a strong factor in determining future behaviour. The more products a customer holds with the bank, the less likely they are to attrite; hence the bank can work on promotional schemes or loyalty programs with additional services to help retain the customers with fewer products.
  • The model built prioritizes recall in order to catch as many attriters as possible, giving the bank a chance to act on the at-risk customers with suitable interventions based on what the risk factors are as discussed above.
  • In conclusion, our model has generalized well on unseen data and able to predict 96.6% of the customers that attrite which gives the opportunity for the bank to preempt the behaviour and take necessary actions.
  • Our model may miss some customers and predict that they will attrite when they in fact will not, meaning some resources may be spent on trying to retain customers. It is a trade off the bank has to make in order to keep the high risk customers at the top of our priorities.
  • Since we have prioritized catching attriting customers and potentially overestimating at-risk customers, the retention strategies should be targeted and careful as to not overwhelm the customers that were not planning to attrite regardless. The bank can focus on more gentle interventions like perks, discounts, financial support, etc. so that even the customers wrongly identified as attriters can benefit from the plan and not be alienated.
